metadata.name: Irregular #47
metadata.description:
Irregular is a generative art project made to loop without an end.
Each iteration creates a random noise distributed grid of points. This base grid is the final static output image. Once created, it enters a deformation loop based on a flow movement, which is distorted and returns to the origin with a breathing rhythm.

Responsive, zoom out browser window and refresh to get a larger output.
's' save the current canvas

Made with love, javascript and p5js
2022 Diego Pintos, see LICENSE.md

An artificially extended process, from hand to screen, from screen to paper, that creates a new kind of mixed media.

metadata.name: Love #201
metadata.description:
We all experience love at different scales, ranging from scarcely perceived instances of kindness to unforgettable affections shown to us by family and friends, pets and partners. Each of these moments link us to the same boundless and enveloping interconnectedness that persists across space and time: the infinite source of our deepest aspirations.

Like the feeling of simple bliss, ‚ÄòLove‚Äô portrays the visceral radiant light and warmth of our innermost joys. By taking a moment to open ourselves up, these swirling worlds of weightless and seemingly infinite brush strokes invite us to slow down and dwell in prismatic intuitive swells.

In doing so, we may find the immense and omnipresent love that needs only our awareness to be felt.

__________

Press 1-9 to load at different scales (1 = 2,000x2,000 (default), 9 = 10,000x10,000)
When zoomed in, once the output is fully loaded, you can click and drag to move around the canvas
Press 'S' to save the image at the current scale
Press 'B' to toggle the background texture on or off
Press 'A' to toggle the loading animation (recommended for very large scales)

Created with p5.js
For third party license information, please see bundle.js.LICENSE.txt
__________

metadata.name: GEOMORPHISM #2
metadata.description:
A 4444 character magic spell for my rayhatching framework to render thinking rocks.

This piece may take some time to render (about 1-3 minutes, depending on hardware). The rendering time is symbolic of the vastness and agelessness of these rock structures, it is recommended to use the rendering time to contemplate deeply the concept of time spans so incredibly long, that to experience them they would have to overwrite your memories several times and thus are impossible to truly comprehend.

To ponder how, if they are so old, how come some of them float? Are these rocks the fixtures and has time and space itself eroded around them?

This project uses an approach called "rejection sampling". This means the program generates a random set of parameters, and then checks/previews how the resulting image would look. It measures the amount of visible objects, light and shadows, and then determines whether these fall into acceptable ranges. If not, it generates a new set of parameters. For certain hashes over a 100 parameter sets may be checked before it accepts the image.

The features of this project are "cliff", "ground", "thing" and "sky". These are not parameters, they are actual measurements of the resulting image, indicating what percentage of the view is occupied.

This piece can be saved as an SVG and plotted. It is recommended to run a path order optimization tool such as vpype or axicli, this will greatly reduce plotting time.

Some options can be changed via the URL:

&w=.25 : The line width in millimetres.
&d=.4 : Line density (multiplier to linewidth).
&h=235 : Page height in millimetres. The aspect ratio is 16:9, for a width of 420mm, suitable for A3 plotting.

The line width is set to 0.25 millimetres to suit most common fine liner pen stroke widths when plotting. 

If you don't intend to plot this piece, perhaps also try rendering it at 0.2 or even 0.1 millimetres line width, for an even more detailed image (it will also take longer to render).

(c) 2022 by Piter Pasma

metadata.name: Glossolalia #32
metadata.description:
This series is ultimately about catharsis. The compositions can be chaotic and maybe even a little messy, but they also can be vibrant and diverse‚Ä¶ which is really what this is trying to celebrate: diversity and expression.

Simply, it‚Äôs about the emotions associated with whatever frees you.

Please see the linked fxtext article (on the main project page) for a more in-depth dissection of the concept. It‚Äôs less of a technical discussion, and more about the experience of the artist, and how it became linked with the feelings they associate with the art.

In live mode:

For higher resolutions, you can append ‚Äú&density=2‚Äù to the url to double the size, ‚Äú&density=3‚Äù to triple, and so on.
(This is highly recommended.)

To adjust grain, you can append ‚Äú&grain=##‚Äù to the url. 40 is the default, and 0 will remove it completely.

metadata.name: Cosmic reaction #86
metadata.description:
As per my daily programming routine, this time I went to combine different circle algorithms, like my last work. This work, by using the optimized algorithm of packing and fields and combining them with a pattern for the inner connection of the circles, presents an artwork with high details that can be seen in large dimensions by plotting it. There are different variations, some of which are more detailed. The colors of some circles, at much higher resolutions, may look very slightly different.
_________________________

To see the artwork in high quality, open it in live view and add ‚Äú&res=1 to 25‚Äù to the URL, This artwork can also be plotted in large dimensions.

Made with p5js.

metadata.name: 3OHA #22
metadata.description:
This work is a representation of complex systems found in both nature and society. The artwork consists of simple recursively divided cells, showcasing the self-similarity that exists in many structures. The texture of each cell resembles the weave of fabric, emphasizing the interconnected nature of these systems. The patterns and structures generated by the artwork follow simple rules, yet the resulting composition is intricate and complex. This artwork highlights the way that simple elements can combine to form more complex systems, and prompts reflection on the underlying structures that shape our world. The texture which resembles fabric or weaved material is not an afterthought but was more the initial purpose of this work.

HALF OF THE MONEY WILL BE DONATED FOR THE EARTHQUAKE RELIEF FUND.

metadata.name: NYC-80 #11
metadata.description:
Even if this work was intended as an abstract study, the crowded, rhythmically repeating structures are reminiscent of the monumental, anonymous appearance of some large cities.
The appearance is determined by naive strong strokes and simple forms that give the picture a strong and self-confident expressiveness reminiscent of the art of the New York art scene of the 80s. The surfaces are deliberately not layered, in order to underline the impenetrability, but also to preserve the abstract painterly element.
